{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1783875877,"nonce":"iA9F2ENj3lUGkIui3AgOttfEil4=","title":"Catalog-based view name resolution to remove the source/alias-collision replan residual","message":"Follow-up to e1d0724 (suppressed projection alias in a view/CTE body clause). That\nfix stores a projection's suppressed `AS` in `ProjectionItem.internal_alias` and\nre-emits it so a column-listed view whose `ORDER BY`/`GROUP BY`/`HAVING` names a\nprojection alias renders valid SQL and round-trips. A residual remains: the reverse\nparser has no source-column catalog, so it cannot always tell a clause's alias\nreference from a same-named source column, and a backend rewrites clause references\non introspection. This makes such a view re-plan a harmless `CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW`\neach run (idempotent, non-destructive; never wrong SQL, meaning preserved) — the same\nconvergence gap the body-unknown view path already accepts.\n\nTwo shapes trigger the residual:\n1. A backend rewrites a clause's alias reference to the underlying expression on\n   deparse. PostgreSQL `pg_get_viewdef` deparses\n   `CREATE VIEW v (n) AS SELECT 1 AS total ORDER BY total` as\n   `SELECT 1 AS n ORDER BY 1::integer` (expression/ordinal, no alias); MySQL expands\n   an expression-alias `ORDER BY`. The introspected body no longer carries the alias,\n   so it differs from the desired model that keeps it.\n2. A source column whose name collides with a computed projection alias. In\n   `SELECT -q.total AS total FROM t q ORDER BY total + 0` (source `t.total` present),\n   a dialect resolves the bare `total` to the source column, but the reverse parser\n   keeps it as an alias reference (it can't see `t`'s columns). Also PostgreSQL\n   `GROUP BY \u003calias\u003e` deparses to the underlying source column.\n\nFix: thread the source relations' column lists (from introspection) into the reverse\nparser's column resolver so a bare clause name resolves to source-column-vs-alias per\neach dialect's rules. This is the epic's flagged name-resolution work\n(`diff.rs:436` exact-PartialEq needs view-output type/name inference); scope it to the\nview-body clause resolver. The typed `#[view]` builder cannot produce the shape (its\nclauses reference only source columns), so exposure is external/hand-authored SQL and\nKDL packages.\n\nRelated: git-bug e1d0724 (parent), acb1c6d (epic: reverse parser + round-trip fidelity).","files":null}]}